\section*{RH $_{\text {NULL }}$ PHENOTYPE}

This is an individual lacking all the representation of Rhesus antigens on the R.B.C. The person is devoid of any Rhesus antigens. It was discovered among the Australian Aborigines due to consanguineous marriages. $\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ individuals are of phenotype and genotype ---/--- (minus minus minus)
The common allele $\mathrm{X}^{1} \mathrm{r}$ is responsible for converting precursor substance I to precursor substance II which is then converted by the Rh genes DCE into Rh antigen DCE/Dce depending on genes inherited.
The more common regulator type of $\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ mutations occur in the RHAG gene that result in complete absence of core Rh complex ( Rh polypeptides and Rh-Ag) that is necessary for the ex-
pression of Rh antigens. The other form of $\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ the amorph type has a normal RHAG gene; however, there is a mutation in each RHCE gene, together with the common deletion of RHD. The $\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ individuals lack the common allele and they instead have the modifier / regulator gene $\mathrm{x}^{0} \mathrm{r} / \mathrm{x}^{0} \mathrm{r}$ which does not convert precursor substance I to precursor substance II. Thus there is no production of Rh antigens. When $\mathrm{x}^{0} \mathrm{r}$ is heterozygous $\mathrm{x}^{0} \mathrm{r} / \mathrm{x}^{1} \mathrm{r}$, partial expression of Rh - antigens results. When $\mathrm{x}^{\circ} \mathrm{r}$ is homozygous, there is complete suppression of Rh gene. $\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ individuals have inherited homozygous $\mathrm{x}^{0} \mathrm{r}$ gene which suppresses the expression of Rh genes.
$\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ phenotype when tested with any or all Rh antibodies CDEce the cells fail to react and they appear to be devoid of Rhesus antigens. However the Rh genes are normal as shown by the fact that $\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ individuals transmit to their offspring functional Rh genes which they inherited from their parents. An individual who is $\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ is considered to be Rh negative because of lack of D antigen
A person with $\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ cannot be transfused with Rh negative blood to avoid contamination of $\mathrm{C}, \mathrm{E}$ antigens. They form allo-antibodies on exposure to rhesus antigens.
$\mathrm{Rh}_{\text {null }}$ individuals present with stomatocytosis, with mild haemolytic process.

