\section*{HEAT ELUTION METHOD:}

\section*{Landsteiner and Muller:}

Principle: Heat_elution uses an increase in temperature to dissociate antibodies from red cells. Mostly used for ABO HDNB.
- Wash the cells (clot) / sensitised six times.
- Make sure the supernatant is removed completely.
- To one volume of packed cells, use one volume of the suspending media (serum or $6 \%$ Bovine albumin).
- Mix well and incubate @ $56^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ in a water bath for about $10-20$ mins agitating the mixture frequently during incubation.
- Immediately transfer the tube to a pre-warm centrifuge bucket at $56^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ at a high speed. (3000 r.p.m.)
- Remove the Hb tinted supernatant and place in another tube. This is the eluate

\section*{RUBINS ETHER METHOD:}
- Wash the cells 4-6 times in Normal saline.
- Add an equal volume of N. saline and mix.
- Add di-ethyl-ether reagent equal to the total volume of cells and N. saline.
- Stopper the test tube and mix by inversion for 1 min .
- The mixture is then incubated @ $37^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ for 30 mins .
- Centrifuge @ 3000 rpm (speed) for 5 mins .
- The tube will have three layers
- The first layer has red cells stroma.
- Second, layer Di-ethyl ether.
- The bottom layer constitutes eluate.

Aspirate and discard the top two layers. OR by use of a long Pasteur pipette access the eluate and aspirate.
Transfer eluate to another tube and incubate @ $37^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ for 30 mins to drive off residuals Diethylether. Or bubble air through at $37^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ for 15 mins .

\section*{Principle}

Di- ethyl ether lyses cells.
Disadvantages eluate is heavily stained with Hb that one might think lysing has not occurred.

\section*{LUI FREEZE-THAW ELUTION:}

PRINCIPLE: As RBC's freeze, extracellular ice crystals form that attract water from their surroundings.
This increases the osmolarity of the remaining extracellular fluid, which then attracts water from the red cells. The red cells shrink, resulting in lysis. As the membranes are disrupted, antibody is dissociated. This method is used for investigation of ABO HDNB.

\section*{Procedure.}

DAT positive red cells washed six times with Normal Saline.
Mix 0.5 mls of red cells to be tested with 3 drops of saline in a test tube.
Cap the test tube, and then rotate the tube to coat the tube wall with cells.
Place the tube in a freezer at ${ }^{-} 20$ to ${ }^{-} 70^{0} \mathrm{C}$ for 10 minutes.
Remove the tube in a freezer and thaw quickly with warm tap water.
Centrifuge for 2 minutes at $900 \times 1000 \times g$
Transfer supernatant (eluate) to a clean test tube and test in parallel with the supernatant saline from last wash.

\section*{COMPATIBILITY TEST OR CROSS MATCH}

Compatibility test is a laboratory procedure to determine ahead of time that there is serology compatibility between a blood donor and the intended recipient. This test is one of the most important tests done in a transfusion service. Great care is necessary because of its importance, since an error in cross match may not be recognized until the recipient has received part or even the entire selected unit of blood with adverse and likely fatal reactions.

\section*{Purpose of performing cross-match:}
1. To detect irregular antibodies in the recipient's serums that are directed against donor's cells. This is known as the major crossmatch
To detect donor's antibodies directed against the recipients r.b.c's. This is minor x-match.
2. To detect errors in ABO grouping
3. To detect errors in labelling, recording or identifying donors or recipients
4. Assurance of maximum benefit for the recipient receiving the blood. This is done by
(i) Preventing transfusion reaction by giving compatible blood to recipient
(ii) Prevent allo-immunization

Cross match does not:
- Ensure normal survival of donors r.b.c's
- Prevent iso-immunization of the pt
- Detect all the ABO grouping errors
- Detect all errors of identification

Transfusion is required in
- Surgical cases
- Anaemic patients; Thalassaemia, S.C.D.
- Haemorrhage / Accident
- H.D.N.B-exchange transfusion
- Maternity cases-elective surgery

