\section*{PLANING AND SETTING OF A BLOOD DONOR CENTRE. \\ (Blood Bank)}

\section*{Roles of donor centre;}
1. Donor recruitment
2. Phlebotomy.
3. Blood screening e.g. blood grouping
4. Preparing of blood products e.g. Fresh Frozen Plasma
5. Advisory centre or Research centre.

\section*{STAFF}
1) The centre should be headed by a qualified staff either a medical technologist or pathologist. The in charge serves as the administrator, public relation adviser and a research worker.
2) Technical staff worker in the centre must have a thorough knowledge of blood donor recruitment. They should make sure that they perform phlebotomy to donors who are fit medically to avoid any undue legal implications.
3) Only people in experience in vene-puncture should perform phlebotomy to donors using aseptic technique. It is important that donors have confidence in the staff.
4) Clerical officers are also essential for record keeping and read other supporting officers for cleaning the place and equipment that does no require any skills.

\section*{THE BUILDING:}
1) The donor, area includes - space for reception (waiting)
2) Counselling room)
3) Phlebotomy area
4) Recovering room.
5) It should be located in an area that has a free and unobstructed flow of traffic.
6) It should have good lighting and ventilation.
7) All surfaces should be of materials that could be easily and thoroughly cleaned.
8) The room for registration and waiting should be arranged to prevent observation of other hospital activities.
9) A private waiting room is always desirable particularly if the centre is in the hospital premises since some people may be discouraged from donating blood after observing other hospital activities.
10) Privacy is desirable for interview and examination of prospective donors. Donors may not give a reliable medical history or may fail to ask questions if other donors, visitors or other blood donor personnel can hear what they are saying. Physical examination cannot be done in open place.
11) The donor bleeding room should be arranged to have the least disturbance either from visitors or non-essential personnel. If possible curtains should be used to separate one donor from the other.
12) Air conditioning may be required during warm humid whether.
13) A canteen may be just adjacent to the bleeding room for a drink and can be combined in an observation room.
14) A separate and private room should be available for treatment of donors who have reactions during or after donation.
15) The centre should have room or area for processing blood and storage purposes.
16) The centre should always have blood taking sets or bags.

Its always important to take detailed information of the donor e.g. address, names, locality, where they work.

\section*{RECRUITMENT OF DONORS:}

In order of the blood donor centre to be able to cope in blood supplies due to increased demand, a blood donor centre should formulate a programme for getting it's own donors. i.e. Voluntary Non remunerated Safe Blood Donors.
Where applicable relatives should be encouraged to donate blood for their patients.
Some of the methods of recruitment of donors is to lecture in schools, colleges and even factories and also through chief's baraza.
There are some people due to superstitious or religious belief shall the responsibility for donating blood. Great effort should be done to educate such a people.
Other mode of blood campaign is thro' posters mass media e.g. T.V, radio(most effective) and even local newspapers.

